[
  {
    "slide_number": 1,
    "lines": [
      "to Systems Programming",
      "Dynamic Memory",
      "\u201cYou are now all sanitation engineers\u201d"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 2,
    "lines": [
      "Memory allocation",
      "\u2022 So far, we have seen two kinds of memory allocation:",
      "// a global variable",
      "int counter = 0;",
      "int main(int argc, char **argv)",
      "{",
      "counter++;",
      "return 0;",
      "}",
      "int foo(int a) {",
      "int x = a + 1;",
      "// local var",
      "return x;",
      "}",
      "int main(int argc, char **argv) {",
      "int y = foo(10);",
      "// local var",
      "return 0;",
      "}",
      "counter is statically allocated",
      "-",
      "allocated when program is loaded",
      "-",
      "deallocated when program exits",
      "-",
      "Memory in the data/bss/text segments",
      "a,x,y are automatically/temporarily allocated",
      "-",
      "allocated when function is called",
      "-",
      "deallocated when function returns",
      "-",
      "Memory in the stack segment"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 3,
    "lines": [
      "We need more flexibility",
      "\u2022 Sometimes we want to allocate memory that:",
      "\u2022 is allocated at runtime (not statically)",
      "\u2022 but persists across multiple function calls (not automatic/temporary)",
      "\u2022 less than the lifetime of the program, longer than the lifetime of a function",
      "\u2022 We want to:",
      "\u2022 Handle data too big to fit on the stack",
      "\u2022 Handle data where its size is not",
      "known in advance",
      "\u2022 Allocate the memory ourselves",
      "\u2022 This is called dynamic memory",
      "// (this is pseudo-C-code)",
      "char* read_file(char* filename) {",
      "int",
      "size = get_file_size(filename);",
      "char* buffer = AllocateMemory(size);",
      "read_file_into_buffer(filename, buffer);",
      "return buffer;",
      "}"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 4,
    "lines": [
      "Dynamic Memory Allocation",
      "\u2022 What we want is dynamically allocated memory",
      "\u2022 We want to explicitly request a new block of memory",
      "\u2022 But how?",
      "\u2022 The language runtime allocates it, perhaps with help from OS",
      "\u2022 Dynamically allocated memory persists until:",
      "\u2022 your code explicitly deallocates it [manual memory management]",
      "\u2022 C, C++, Rust",
      "\u2022 a garbage collector collects it [automatic memory management]",
      "\u2022 Java, Python, Go",
      "\u2022 C requires you to manually manage dynamic memory",
      "\u2022 gives you more control and performance, but can cause headaches",
      "\u2022 C has no garbage collection. YOU ARE THE GARBAGE COLLECTOR"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 5,
    "lines": [
      "Aside: Garbage Collection, in general",
      "\u2022 In some languages like Java, you can dynamically allocate objects using the",
      "built-in \u201cnew\u201d function of the Java runtime environment",
      "\u2022 Stays in memory until an invisible process behind the scenes frees.",
      "\u2022 This invisible process is called garbage collection",
      "\u2022 Typically done in the background by a background process",
      "\u2022 Tracks scope, use, reference, and other metadata to know when to reap objects",
      "\u2022 Pros: a large class of memory bugs avoided",
      "\u2022 dereferencing dangling pointers, memory leaks, double freeing of memory, \u2026",
      "\u2022 Cons: unpredictable performance",
      "\u2022 garbage collection can start at an arbitrary time and slow down the program*",
      "String str1 = new String(\u201cThis is a text string\u201d);"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 6,
    "lines": [
      "Dynamic Memory Allocation",
      "0x00000000",
      "0xFFFFFFFF",
      "OS kernel [protected]",
      "stack (automatic)",
      "read/write segment",
      ".data, .bss (static)",
      "read-only segment",
      ".text, .rodata (static)",
      "\u2022 Remember, we want dynamic memory to allow us to:",
      "\u2022 \u2026 allocate an arbitrary number of bytes",
      "\u2022 \u2026 use and release (or \u201cfree\u201d) memory at any point",
      "\u2022 Non-static, non-automatic",
      "\u2022 \u2026 not interfere with our existing segments",
      "\u2022 Given these wants, where do we place said data?"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 7,
    "lines": [
      "The Heap",
      "\u2022 The heap is a segment in virtual memory that:",
      "\u2022 holds a large pool of unused memory that is used for",
      "dynamically allocated data",
      "\u2022 Unordered\u2026",
      "\u2022 Allocating new memory doesn\u2019t necessarily mean new",
      "memory will be \u201cabove\u201d or \u201cbefore\u201d other dynamic memory",
      "\u2022 \u2026but structured (usually)",
      "\u2022 Most libraries inject hidden metadata about how big a",
      "dynamic allocation is (473 Topic)",
      "\u2022 Grows from low addresses to high addresses",
      "0x00000000",
      "0xFFFFFFFF",
      "OS kernel [protected]",
      "stack (automatic)",
      "read/write segment",
      ".data, .bss (static)",
      "read-only segment",
      ".text, .rodata (static)",
      "heap (dynamic)"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 8,
    "lines": [
      "The heap, at a glance",
      "\u2022 Ultimately the kernel is responsible",
      "for allocating memory to a process",
      "\u2022 Every program begins with a certain",
      "amount of memory in its heap",
      "\u2022 The top of the heap is known",
      "and the program break.",
      "\u2022 The program break gets moved up",
      "and down as memory is allocated",
      "and deallocated from the heap.",
      "0x00000000",
      "0xFFFFFFFF",
      "OS kernel [protected]",
      "stack (automatic)",
      "read/write segment",
      ".data, .bss (static)",
      "read-only segment",
      ".text, .rodata (static)",
      "heap (dynamic)"
    ]
  },
