  {
    "slide_number": 10,
    "lines": [
      "brk() and sbrk() System Calls",
      "\u2022 The functions are system calls to request a change in program break",
      "\u2022 void* brk( void* ptr ) \u2013 requests the program break to be set at",
      "the address ptr",
      "\u2022 This is an absolute pointer, so very dangerous",
      "\u2022 Calling brk(NULL) returns the current program break",
      "\u2022 void* sbrk( int inc ) \u2013 requests the program break to increment",
      "inc bytes upwards or downwards",
      "\u2022 A positive inc allocates new memory",
      "\u2022 A negative inc frees memory",
      "These functions are declared in the system library unistd.h"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 11,
    "lines": [
      "Are we going to use these calls?",
      "\u2022 In short, no.",
      "\u2022 In this class we will not directly call these system calls, we will use a system library",
      "\u2022 In 473, yes.",
      "\u2022 You will implement your own dynamic memory allocation library which directly uses",
      "these system calls",
      "\u2022 Then why tell us?",
      "\u2022 The libraries we will use make these calls for us; they are wrappers / abstractions.",
      "\u2022 Important to understand that you are still making system calls!"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 12,
    "lines": [
      "Dynamic Memory Allocation in C",
      "\u2022 So how do we actually request memory dynamically from our operating",
      "system in C?",
      "\u2022 Using the following system library in stdlib.h",
      "void* malloc(size_t size);",
      "void* calloc(size_t nmemb, size_t size);",
      "void* realloc(void* ptr, size_t size)",
      "void  free(void* ptr);"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 13,
    "lines": [
      "C and malloc",
      "\u2022 malloc allocates a block of memory of the given size in bytes",
      "\u2022 returns a pointer to the first byte of raw memory (returns a void*)",
      "\u2022 It\u2019s best practice to cast the return for readability",
      "\u2022 Though it is not really necessary",
      "\u2022 void pointers are automatically promoted/casted",
      "\u2022 malloc returns NULL if the memory could not be allocated (very rare)",
      "\u2022 You\u2019ll typically use sizeof() to calculate the size you need",
      "// allocate a 10 element int array",
      "int* arr = (int*)malloc(10 * sizeof(int));",
      "if (arr == NULL) return -1;",
      "arr[0] = 5;",
      "arr[3] = 123;",
      "void* malloc(size_t bytes)",
      "// allocate a single float",
      "float* my_float = (float*)malloc(sizeof(float));",
      "if (my_float == NULL) return -1;",
      "*my_float = 3.14159;"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 14,
    "lines": [
      "Dynamically allocated types",
      "\u2022 You can malloc() any type; primitive, struct, etc\u2026",
      "\u2022 Allows you to make functions that allocate memory / create objects for you!",
      "typedef struct {",
      "double real;",
      "// real component",
      "double imag;",
      "// imaginary component",
      "} complex_t,",
      "complex_t* create_complex(double real, double imag) {",
      "complex_t* newcomp = (complex_t*)malloc(sizeof(complex_t));",
      "if (newcomp == NULL) return NULL;",
      "newcomp->real = real;",
      "newcomp->imag = imag;",
      "return newcomp;",
      "}",
      "void main(void) {",
      "complex_t* sqneg1 = create_complex(0, 1);",
      "sqneg1->real == 0; // evals true",
      "sqneg1->imag == 1; // evals true",
      "}"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 15,
    "lines": [
      "But didn\u2019t we say not to do this?",
      "\u2022 Okay to return a pointer to memory that is not managed by your scope",
      "\u2022 NOT OKAY TO RETURN A POINTER TO A LOCAL VARIABLE (WHY?)",
      "int* max(int* a, int* b) {",
      "return (*a > *b) ? a : b;",
      "}",
      "void main(void) {",
      "int x = 5, y = 6;",
      "printf(\"max of %d and %d is %d\\n\", x, y, *max(&x, &y));",
      "}",
      "int* foo(void) {",
      "int x = 5;",
      "return &x;",
      "}",
      "int main(void) {",
      "printf(\"%d\\n\", *foo());",
      "}",
      "REMEMBER: MALLOC MEMORY IS NOT STACK ALLOCATED,",
      "ITS ON THE HEAP (NOT YOUR \u201cSCOPE\u201d)!"
    ]
  },
