  {
    "slide_number": 26,
    "lines": [
      "C and calloc",
      "\u2022 When you use malloc, the memory is uninitialized, contains garbage",
      "\u2022 If you want to zero-out the memory, you can alternatively use calloc",
      "\u2022 Returns an array of nmemb members, each of size bytes",
      "\u2022 Memory is zeroed out (all bytes have the value 0x0)",
      "\u2022 Performance hit, but preferred for non-performance-critical code",
      "void* calloc(size_t nmemb, size_t bytes);",
      "// allocate a 10 element int array initialized to 0",
      "int* arr = (int*)calloc(10, sizeof(int));",
      "if (arr == NULL) return -1;",
      "arr[0..9] == 0; // all true"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 27,
    "lines": [
      "Memory Operations",
      "\u2022 Given that malloc and calloc return raw memory pointers, it is useful to treat",
      "these regions as byte-element buffers (when left uncast)",
      "\u2022 Given two raw memory addresses, we can perform byte-wise memory",
      "operations:",
      "\u2022 Initialize memory byte-wise to something (set all buffer bytes to be 0x3)",
      "\u2022 Compare memory byte-wise (is buffer 1 == buffer 2)",
      "\u2022 Copy memory byte-wise (set buffer 1 = buffer 2)",
      "\u2022 Some of this should conceptually be similar to what you\u2019ve already done in",
      "homework / used in other standard libraries (such as string.h)"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 28,
    "lines": [
      "Filling memory",
      "\u2022 memset fills n bytes of buf memory with a given constant byte value",
      "void* memset(void* buf, unsigned char value, size_t n);",
      "Returns the buffer that was passed in.",
      "char a[4] = {0, 1, 2, 3};",
      "memset(a, 0, 4);",
      "// what are the contents of a now?",
      "int b[4] = {0, 1, 2, 3};",
      "memset(b, 10, 4);",
      "// what are the contents of b now? Be careful!"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 29,
    "lines": [
      "\u2022 We often want to compare buffers to see if they match",
      "\u2022 And sometimes also to see if one is byte-wise smaller or larger",
      "\u2022 memcmp compares first n bytes of buffers",
      "\u2022 The comparison function returns:",
      "\u2022 A negative integer if buf1 is less than buf2",
      "\u2022 Zero if buf1 is equal to buf2",
      "\u2022 A positive integer is buf1 greater than buf2",
      "Comparing memory",
      "int memcmp(void* buf1, void* buf2, size_t n);",
      "memcpy(dest, src, n)",
      "is kinda like",
      "dest = src"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 30,
    "lines": [
      "Copying memory",
      "\u2022 memcpy copies one memory region to another byte-wise",
      "\u2022 Copy n bytes from src (\u201csource\u201d) buffer to dst (\u201cdestination\u201d) buffer",
      "char buf1[8] = { 'a', 'a', 'a', \u2018a\u2019, 'a', 'a', 'a', 'a' };",
