  {
    "slide_number": 42,
    "lines": [
      "Memory Safety Concerns",
      "\u2022 There are several things you need to watch out for when dealing with memory in C",
      "(usually dealing with dynamic memory but not always)",
      "\u2022 Out of bounds (OOB) errors (arrays/pointers/arithmetic)",
      "\u2022 You\u2019ve seen this already more or less\u2026",
      "\u2022 Use after free (UAF) (dereferencing a dangling pointer that was not NULL\u2019d)",
      "\u2022 Always NULL your pointer after free / do not reuse the pointer/reference/variable",
      "\u2022 Double free (DF) (freeing a dangling pointer that was previously already freed)",
      "\u2022 Always NULL your pointer after free / do not reuse the pointer/reference/variable",
      "\u2022 Invalid free (IF) (freeing a non-dynamic memory pointer (such as a stack variable))",
      "\u2022 You can\u2019t avoid using free; Not freeing allocated variables in time is problematic / antithetical",
      "\u2022 \u201cMemory leaks\u201d"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 43,
    "lines": [
      "Memory leak",
      "\u2022 A memory leak happens when code fails to deallocate dynamically",
      "allocate memory that will no longer be used",
      "// assume we have access to functions FileLen,",
      "// ReadFileIntoBuffer, and NumWordsInString.",
      "int NumWordsInFile(char *filename) {",
      "char *filebuf = malloc(FileLen(filename)+1);",
      "if (filebuf == NULL)",
      "return -1;",
      "ReadFileIntoBuffer(filename, filebuf);",
      "// leak! we never free(filebuf) or pass a reference to someone else",
      "return NumWordsInString(filebuf);",
      "}"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 44,
    "lines": [
      "Implications of a leak?",
      "\u2022 A program\u2019s virtual memory will keep growing",
      "\u2022 for short-lived programs, this might be OK",
      "\u2022 for long-lived programs, this:",
      "\u2022 might slow down over time (caching issues, swap space, etc\u2026)",
      "\u2022 might exhaust all available memory and crash (OOM)",
      "\u2022 other programs might get starved of memory (silent denial of service)",
      "\u2022 in some cases, you might prefer to leak memory than to corrupt memory",
      "with a buggy free()*********",
      "\u2022 you\u2019re not far enough in programming yet to make this call\u2026 \u263a"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 45,
    "lines": [
      "How to avoid memory leaks",
      "\u2022 You can ask a very simple question to avoid memory leaks.",
      "\u2022 Who is responsible for this memory?",
      "\u2022 If you are passing a malloc\u2019d pointer back to a caller, then it is the caller\u2019s",
      "responsibility to free or call a free-like method",
      "\u2022 If you are NOT passing a reference to the malloc\u2019d pointer back to the caller, then it is",
      "YOUR responsibility to free the memory before your function ends.",
      "\u2022 Not too complex"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 46,
    "lines": [
      "Finding Memory Safety Issues",
      "\u2022 GCC has some static memory safety checks",
      "\u2022 Address sanitization is a fast instrumentation tool within GCC",
      "\u2022 gcc \u2013fsanitize=address foo.c \u2013o foo",
      "\u2022 Will tell you about OOB, UAF, DF, and some others when you run the program!",
      "\u2022 GDB can inspect memory and use watch points to find issues",
      "\u2022 Valgrind is a purpose-built debugger",
      "for identifying memory leaks and issues",
      "\u2022 More heavyweight than GCC\u2019s address sanitizer",
      "\u2022 valgrind \u2013v \u2013\u2013leak-check=full \u2013\u2013errors-for-leak-kinds=all ./a.out"
    ]
  },
  {
    "slide_number": 47,
    "lines": [
      "Memory Safety, In Short",
      "\u2022 Always check the return status of malloc/calloc/realloc calls",
      "\u2022 Always NULL pointers after they are freed",
      "\u2022 Understand who is responsible to free memory",
      "\u2022 Match every malloc with exactly one free!",
      "\u2022 When in doubt, document with comments!",
      "\u2022 Free in reverse order of allocation",
      "\u2022 Useful for nested structures (hint hint)",
      "\u2022 Use the heap for dynamic or large objects, use the stack for small/temporary"
    ]
  },
